<exercises xml:id="ex-Continuity">
    <exercise>
        <p>
            Explain how the definition of continuity (<xref ref="def-ContinuousAtPoint"/>) describes a function being <q>connected to itself</q> at the point.
        </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <p>
            What does it mean for a function to be continuous on the left at a point? What about on the right?
        </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Use the definition of continuity at a point to determine whether each function is continuous at the point listed. If it is not, is the function continuous on one side at the point? Explain.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>f(x) =
                        \begin{cases}
                          4x+1 \amp \text{if } x\lt 1\\
                          x^2+5 \amp \text{if } x\geq 1
                        \end{cases}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Is <m>f(x)</m> continuous at <m>x=1</m>?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 1} f(x)</m> doesn't exist.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>f(1)=6</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                    This function is not continuous at this point, since
                    <me>
                        \lim_{x\to 1} f(x) \neq f(1)
                    </me>.
                    But, it is continuous on the right side, since 
                    <me>
                        \lim_{x\to 1^+} f(x) = f(1)
                    </me>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>g(x) =
                        \begin{cases}
                          6x^2-2 \amp \text{if } x\lt0\\
                          4 \amp \text{if } x=0\\
                          1-3\cos(x) \amp \text{if } x\gt 0
                        \end{cases}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Is <m>g(x)</m> continuous at <m>x=0</m>?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 0} g(x) = -2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>g(0)=4</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                    This function is not continuous at this point, since
                    <me>
                        \lim_{x\to -2} g(x) \neq g(-2)
                    </me>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>h(x) =
                        \begin{cases}
                          \left(\dfrac{x^2-1}{x+1}\right) \amp \text{if } x\neq -1\\
                          -2 \amp\text{if } x=-1
                        \end{cases}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Is <m>h(x)</m> continuous at <m>x=-1</m>?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to -1} h(x) = -2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>h(-1)=-2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                    This function is continuous at this point, since
                    <me>
                        \lim_{x\to -1} h(x) = h(-1)
                    </me>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Find the values of <m>a</m> that make the function continuous at the point that is listed. If no such value of <m>a</m> exists, say so and explain why.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>f(x) =
                        \begin{cases}
                          x -6\amp \text{if } x\lt3\\
                          ax^2+1 \amp \text{if } x\geq 3
                        \end{cases}</m> at <m>x=3</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>a=-\dfrac{2}{9}</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>f(x) =
                        \begin{cases}
                          \dfrac{x^2-4}{x+2} \amp \text{if } x\neq -2\\
                          a \amp \text{if } x=-2
                        \end{cases}</m> at <m>x=-2</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>a=-4</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Use the properties of composition and continuity to evaluate the following limits.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 0} \left(\sin\left(e^{\sqrt{x^2}}\right)\right)</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \lim_{x\to 0} \left(\sin\left(e^{\sqrt{x^2}}\right)\right)\amp = \sin\left(e^{\sqrt{\lim_{x\to 0} x^2}}\right)</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \sin(1)</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 0} \ln\left(\dfrac{\cos(x^2)}{x^2+1}\right)</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \lim_{x\to 0} \ln\left(\dfrac{\cos(x^2)}{x^2+1}\right)\amp = \ln\left(\dfrac{\cos(\lim_{x\to 0} x^2)}{\lim_{x\to 0}(x^2+1)}\right)</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp =0</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 0} \sqrt[3]{\dfrac{x}{\sqrt{16x+1}-1}}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\lim_{x\to 0} \sqrt[3]{\dfrac{x}{\sqrt{16x+1}-1}} \amp = \sqrt[3]{\lim_{x\to 0} \left(\dfrac{x}{\sqrt{16x+1}-1}\right)}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{2}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
        <p>
            <q>Even a broken clock is right twice a day,</q> is a common phrase used to say that even an unreliable person can have a good point on accident. Explain how we can use the Intermediate Value Theorem to prove that a broken (analog) clock is guaranteed right twice per day. (Here, we're assuming that <q>broken</q> means stuck.)
        </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Explain why this argument doesn't work to show that an unreliable person will be guaranteed to have a good point on accident.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Prove that at some point in your life you were exactly <m>\pi</m> feet tall.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
</exercises>